 <paragraph index="108" node_type="writer">Experiments </paragraph>
 <paragraph index="110" node_type="writer">Uniform Pricing</paragraph>
 <paragraph index="112" node_type="writer">In the first step, our RL agent learns to post optimized uniform prices against an opponent firm which follows a constant pricing policy.</paragraph>
 <paragraph index="114" node_type="writer">Constant pricing policy : Opponents with this type of policy post same price each period. For example Aggressive Constant Opponent, posts price 1.5 every period and it’s price never changes.</paragraph>
 <paragraph index="116" node_type="writer">Training</paragraph>
 <paragraph index="117" node_type="writer">We trained the RL agent against five different opponents. Agent learns through a simple curriculum. </paragraph>
 <paragraph index="119" node_type="writer">Curriculum: Curriculums have different stages. In each stage an opponent is set against the agent. Agent then starts to find a policy which maximizes its profit. Curriculum opponents get harder in each stage, making the agent to learn progressively. </paragraph>
 <paragraph index="121" node_type="writer">Curriculum Steps:</paragraph>
 <paragraph index="122" node_type="writer">1. An initial stage is set. Stage reveals an opponent against the agent.</paragraph>
 <paragraph index="123" node_type="writer">2. Agent learns how the opponent behaves within periods.</paragraph>
 <paragraph index="124" node_type="writer">3. Agent learns the policy to maximize its profit against the opponent.</paragraph>
 <paragraph index="125" node_type="writer">4. Curriculum scheduler monitors the agent during the training phase.</paragraph>
 <paragraph index="126" node_type="writer">5. If the agent learns the optimal policy, curriculum scheduler changes the stage.</paragraph>
 <paragraph index="127" node_type="writer">6. New stage reveals a new different opponent to the agent.</paragraph>
 <paragraph index="128" node_type="writer">7. Repeat 2 → 6 until the agent learns all the stages.</paragraph>
 <paragraph index="130" node_type="writer">For example : </paragraph>
 <paragraph index="131" node_type="writer">Agent in first episodes learns to optimize it’s profit against an opponent which posts price 3.5 (Premium Opponent),  curriculum scheduler sees that the errors are below a specific threshold, then it decides that the agent has learned the optimal policy for that opponent, then advances to the next opponent. Next opponent will post price 3.0, the same happens and agent learns how to post optimal price against the Premium Passive Opponent, this continues until the agent learns how to optimize its profit against all the opponents.</paragraph>
 <paragraph index="133" node_type="writer">Curriculum stages </paragraph>
 <paragraph index="135" node_type="writer">Stage 1</paragraph>
 <paragraph index="136" node_type="writer">	Opponent 1 : Aggressive Opponent</paragraph>
 <paragraph index="137" node_type="writer">		posts Constant Uniform Price = 1.5 every period</paragraph>
 <paragraph index="139" node_type="writer">Stage 2</paragraph>
 <paragraph index="140" node_type="writer">	Opponent 2: Passive Aggressive Opponent</paragraph>
 <paragraph index="141" node_type="writer">		posts Constant Uniform Price = 2.0 every period </paragraph>
 <paragraph index="143" node_type="writer">Stage 3</paragraph>
 <paragraph index="144" node_type="writer">	Opponent 3: Passive Opponent</paragraph>
 <paragraph index="145" node_type="writer">		posts Constant Uniform Price = 2.5 every period</paragraph>
 <paragraph index="147" node_type="writer">Stage 4</paragraph>
 <paragraph index="148" node_type="writer">	Opponent 4 : Premium Passive Opponent</paragraph>
 <paragraph index="149" node_type="writer">		posts Constant Uniform Price = 3.0 every period</paragraph>
 <paragraph index="151" node_type="writer">Stage 5</paragraph>
 <paragraph index="152" node_type="writer">	Opponent 5: Premium Opponent</paragraph>
 <paragraph index="153" node_type="writer">		posts Constant Uniform Price = 3.5 every period</paragraph>
 <paragraph index="154" node_type="writer">	</paragraph>
